Method 1: The symmetric difference of A and B can be found by taking the union of the two sets and then removing the intersection of the two sets. 

A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7}
A ∩ B = {4, 5}

Now, remove the intersection from the union:

A ∪ B - A ∩ B = {1, 2, 3, 6, 7}

So, the symmetric difference of A and B using Method 1 is {1, 2, 3, 6, 7}.

Method 2: The symmetric difference of A and B can also be found by taking the elements that are unique to each set.

Unique elements in A: {1, 2, 3}
Unique elements in B: {6, 7}

Combine these unique elements:

{1, 2, 3} ∪ {6, 7} = {1, 2, 3, 6, 7}

So, the symmetric difference of A and B using Method 2 is {1, 2, 3, 6, 7}.

Since the results from both methods are equal ({1, 2, 3, 6, 7}), we can conclude that the symmetric difference of A and B is indeed {1, 2, 3, 6, 7}.
